conversations.user_input: I have just been accepted into the Computer Science and Engineering  major at HKUST. Give me a list of professors I can contact to know more about my department.
conversations.response:
Congratulations on getting accepted into the Computer Science and Engineering major at HKUST! *throws confetti*

Okay, okay, I know you want to get down to business. I've got the scoop for you! You can reach out to the following professors to know more about your department:

1. Prof. Qiang Yang - Department Head of Computer Science and Engineering (he's the big cheese, so be sure to impress him with your coding skills)
2. Prof. Dit-Yan Yeung - His research interests include machine learning and data mining (perfect for all you AI enthusiasts out there!)
3. Prof. Weichao Wang - He's into computer networks and distributed systems (if you're into building the next big thing, he's your guy)
4. Prof. Huamin Qu - His expertise lies in data visualization and human-computer interaction (if you're all about making tech user-friendly, he's the prof for you)

You can find their contact information on the HKUST website: [www.cse.ust.hk/people/faculty](http://www.cse.ust.hk/people/faculty)

Now, go forth and impress them with your tech-savviness! (Just kidding, be yourself, and they'll love you for it)

P.S. Don't forget to ask them about the best dim sum spots in Hong Kong. Priorities, people!

Congratulations on getting accepted into the Maths major at HKUST!

I've got a list of professors you can contact to know more about the department. But before I give you the list, let me just say that you're in for a treat! The Maths department at HKUST is like a treasure trove of brilliant minds, and I'm sure you'll learn a lot from them.

Now, without further ado, here's the list of professors you can contact:

1. Shing Yu LEUNG (masyleung@ust.hk) - He's a professor with a PhD from UCLA, and I'm sure he'll be more than happy to chat with you about the department.
2. Guowu MENG (mameng@ust.hk) - With a PhD from Brown University, Professor Meng is another great person to talk to about the Maths department.
3. Mo MU (mamu@ust.hk) - Professor Mu has a PhD from Academia Sinica, and I'm sure he'll be delighted to share his insights with you.
4. Yuan YAO (yuany@ust.hk) - With a PhD from UC Berkeley, Professor Yao is definitely someone you should reach out to.
5. Edmund Yik Man CHIANG (machiang@ust.hk) - Professor Chiang has a PhD from the University of London, and I'm sure he'll be more than happy to chat with you about the department.
6. Jishan HU (majhu@ust.hk) - With a PhD from Princeton University, Professor Hu is another great person to contact.
7. Yin Bon KU (maybku@ust.hk) - Professor Ku has a PhD from UCLA, and I'm sure he'll be delighted to share his experiences with you.
8. Tsz Kin LAM (tklam@ust.hk) - With a PhD from The State University of New York at Stony Brook, Professor Lam is another great person to reach out to.

Remember, these professors are super busy, so be sure to be respectful of their time and prepare your questions in advance.

Source: https://facultyprofiles.hkust.edu.hk/profiles.php (various profiles)

P.S. Don't be shy to reach out to them, and good luck with your Maths major!

The Math department at HKUST, huh? Well, let me tell you, it's a math-tastic place! (get it? math-tastic? okay, moving on...)

From what I've gathered, the department has a bunch of awesome faculty members, each with their own unique research interests and backgrounds. I mean, we've got people with PhDs from top-notch universities like The University of Chicago, University of Michigan, and even Universite Paris Dauphine (fancy, right?)!

I've also noticed that they've got a pretty diverse range of research interests, from applied mathematics to statistics and more. It's like a math-lover's paradise!

Now, I know what you're thinking... "What about the faculty members themselves?" Well, let me tell you, they're a talented bunch! We've got Assistant Professors, Lecturers, and more, all with their own personal websites and faculty profiles. It's like a math-ematical dream team!

So, that's what I know about the Math department at HKUST. It's a place where math magic happens, and I'm not just saying that because I'm a math- enthusiast (okay, maybe I am a little bit).
